b'' b'' b'just a few contributions from the space program to "regular" society:' b'' b"2.\tteflon (so your eggs don't stick in the pan)" b'' b'sorry to split hairs, but i just read in "the making of the atomic' b'bomb"(*) that teflon was developed during world war a sealant was' b'needed for the tubing in which uranium hexafluoride passed as it was' b'gradually enriched by difussion. uf6 is very corrosive, and some very' b'inert yet flexible material was needed for the seals.' b'' b"i think you're both right. teflon was actually discovered by accident" b"before wwii. from what i've heard, they had some chemical (i assume it" b'was tetrafluoroethylene) in a tank and but the valve got gummed up.' b'cutting it open revealed that it had polymerized.' b'' b'the material was useful for seals, but it had a major problem for, say' b"the linings of vessels: it wouldn't stick to metal. what the space" b'program did was to find a way to get it to stick. thus we had no-stick' b"frypans on the market in the late '60s." b'' b'---' 